#: ../../../faq.rst:2
msgid "Frequently asked questions"
msgstr "常見問題"

#: ../../../faq.rst:5
msgid "What is the equivalent to this thing from bash (or other shells)?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:7
msgid "See :ref:`Fish for bash users <fish_for_bash_users>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:10
msgid "How do I set or clear an environment variable?"
msgstr "我要如何設定或清除環境變數？"

#: ../../../faq.rst:11
msgid "Use the :doc:`set <cmds/set>` command::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:13
msgid ""
"set -x key value # typically set -gx key value\n"
"set -e key"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:16
msgid ""
"Since fish 3.1 you can set an environment variable for just one command "
"using the ``key=value some command`` syntax, like in other shells.  The two "
"lines below behave identically - unlike other shells, fish will output "
"``value`` both times::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:18
msgid ""
"key=value echo $key\n"
"begin; set -lx key value; echo $key; end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:21
msgid ""
"Note that \"exported\" is not a :ref:`scope <variables-scope>`, but an "
"additional bit of state. A variable can be global and exported or local and "
"exported or even universal and exported. Typically it makes sense to make an "
"exported variable global."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:24
msgid "How do I check whether a variable is defined?"
msgstr "我要如何檢查變數是否已定義？"

#: ../../../faq.rst:26
msgid ""
"Use ``set -q var``.  For example, ``if set -q var; echo variable defined; "
"end``.  To check multiple variables you can combine with ``and`` and ``or`` "
"like so::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:28
msgid ""
"if set -q var1; or set -q var2\n"
"    echo either variable defined\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:32
msgid ""
"Keep in mind that a defined variable could also be empty, either by having "
"no elements (if set like ``set var``) or only empty elements (if set like "
"``set var \"\"``). Read on for how to deal with those."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:36
msgid "How do I check whether a variable is not empty?"
msgstr "我要如何檢查變數是否不為空？"

#: ../../../faq.rst:38
msgid ""
"Use ``string length -q -- $var``.  For example, ``if string length -q -- "
"$var; echo not empty; end``.  Note that ``string length`` will interpret a "
"list of multiple variables as a disjunction (meaning any/or)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:40
msgid ""
"if string length -q -- $var1 $var2 $var3\n"
"    echo at least one of these variables is not empty\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:44
msgid ""
"Alternatively, use ``test -n \"$var\"``, but remember that **the variable "
"must be double-quoted**.  For example, ``if test -n \"$var\"; echo not "
"empty; end``. The ``test`` command provides its own and (-a) and or (-o)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:46
msgid ""
"if test -n \"$var1\" -o -n \"$var2\" -o -n \"$var3\"\n"
"    echo at least one of these variables is not empty\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:51
msgid ""
"If you want to know if a variable has *no elements*, use ``set -q var[1]``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:55
msgid "Why doesn't ``set -Ux`` (exported universal variables) seem to work?"
msgstr "為什麼 ``set -Ux``（匯出的通用變數）似乎不起作用？"

#: ../../../faq.rst:56
msgid "A global variable of the same name already exists."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:58
msgid ""
"Environment variables such as ``EDITOR`` or ``TZ`` can be set universally "
"using ``set -Ux``.  However, if there is an environment variable already set "
"before fish starts (such as by login scripts or system administrators), it "
"is imported into fish as a global variable. The :ref:`variable scopes "
"<variables-scope>` are searched from the \"inside out\", which means that "
"local variables are checked first, followed by global variables, and finally "
"universal variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:64
msgid ""
"This means that the global value takes precedence over the universal value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:66
msgid ""
"To avoid this problem, consider changing the setting which fish inherits. If "
"this is not possible, add a statement to your :ref:`configuration file "
"<configuration>` (usually ``~/.config/fish/config.fish``)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:70
msgid "set -gx EDITOR vim"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:73
msgid ""
"How do I run a command every login? What's fish's equivalent to .bashrc or ."
"profile?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:74
msgid ""
"Edit the file ``~/.config/fish/config.fish`` [#]_, creating it if it does "
"not exist (Note the leading period)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:76
msgid ""
"Unlike .bashrc and .profile, this file is always read, even in non-"
"interactive or login shells."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:78
msgid ""
"To do something only in interactive shells, check ``status is-interactive`` "
"like::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:80
msgid ""
"if status is-interactive\n"
"    # use the coolbeans theme\n"
"    fish_config theme choose coolbeans\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:85
msgid ""
"The \"~/.config\" part of this can be set via $XDG_CONFIG_HOME, that's just "
"the default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:88
msgid "How do I set my prompt?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:89
msgid ""
"The prompt is the output of the ``fish_prompt`` function. Put it in ``~/."
"config/fish/functions/fish_prompt.fish``. For example, a simple prompt is::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:91
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    set_color $fish_color_cwd\n"
"    echo -n (prompt_pwd)\n"
"    set_color normal\n"
"    echo -n ' > '\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:99
msgid ""
"You can also use the Web configuration tool, :doc:`fish_config <cmds/"
"fish_config>`, to preview and choose from a gallery of sample prompts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:101
msgid "Or you can use fish_config from the commandline::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:103
msgid ""
"> fish_config prompt show\n"
"# displays all the prompts fish ships with\n"
"> fish_config prompt choose disco\n"
"# loads the disco prompt in the current shell\n"
"> fish_config prompt save\n"
"# makes the change permanent"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:110
msgid ""
"If you want to modify your existing prompt, you can use :doc:`funced <cmds/"
"funced>` and :doc:`funcsave <cmds/funcsave>` like::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:112
msgid ""
">_ funced fish_prompt\n"
"# This opens up your editor (set in $EDITOR).\n"
"# Modify the function,\n"
"# save the file and repeat to your liking.\n"
"# Once you are happy with it:\n"
">_ funcsave fish_prompt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:119
msgid ""
"This also applies to :doc:`fish_right_prompt <cmds/fish_right_prompt>` and :"
"doc:`fish_mode_prompt <cmds/fish_mode_prompt>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:122
msgid "Why does my prompt show a ``[I]``?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:124
msgid ""
"That's the :doc:`fish_mode_prompt <cmds/fish_mode_prompt>`. It is displayed "
"by default when you've activated vi mode using ``fish_vi_key_bindings``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:126
msgid ""
"If you haven't activated vi mode on purpose, you might have installed a "
"third-party theme or plugin that does it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:128
msgid ""
"If you want to change or disable this display, modify the "
"``fish_mode_prompt`` function, for instance via :doc:`funced <cmds/funced>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:131
msgid "How do I customize my syntax highlighting colors?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:132
msgid ""
"Use the web configuration tool, :doc:`fish_config <cmds/fish_config>`, or "
"alter the :ref:`fish_color family of environment variables <variables-"
"color>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:134
msgid "You can also use ``fish_config`` on the commandline, like::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:136
msgid ""
"> fish_config theme show\n"
"# to demonstrate all the colorschemes\n"
"> fish_config theme choose coolbeans\n"
"# to load the \"coolbeans\" theme\n"
"> fish_config theme save\n"
"# to make the change permanent"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:144
msgid "How do I change the greeting message?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:145
msgid ""
"Change the value of the variable ``fish_greeting`` or create a :doc:"
"`fish_greeting <cmds/fish_greeting>` function. For example, to remove the "
"greeting use::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:147
msgid "set -U fish_greeting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:149
msgid "Or if you prefer not to use a universal variable, use::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:151
msgid "set -g fish_greeting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:153
msgid "in :ref:`config.fish <configuration>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:156
msgid "How do I run a command from history?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:157
msgid ""
"Type some part of the command, and then hit the :kbd:`↑` (up) or :kbd:`↓` "
"(down) arrow keys to navigate through history matches, or press :kbd:"
"`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`R` to open the history in a searchable pager. In this "
"pager you can press :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`R` or :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :"
"kbd:`S` to move to older or younger history respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:159
msgid ""
"Additional default key bindings include :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`P` (up) "
"and :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`N` (down). See :ref:`Searchable command "
"history <history-search>` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:162
msgid "Why doesn't history substitution (\"!$\" etc.) work?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:163
msgid ""
"Because history substitution is an awkward interface that was invented "
"before interactive line editing was even possible. Instead of adding this "
"pseudo-syntax, fish opts for nice history searching and recall features.  "
"Switching requires a small change of habits: if you want to modify an old "
"line/word, first recall it, then edit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:165
msgid ""
"As a special case, most of the time history substitution is used as ``sudo !!"
"``. In that case just press :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`S`, and it will recall "
"your last commandline with ``sudo`` prefixed (or toggle a ``sudo`` prefix on "
"the current commandline if there is anything)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:167
msgid "In general, fish's history recall works like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:169
msgid ""
"Like other shells, the Up arrow, :kbd:`↑` recalls whole lines, starting from "
"the last executed line.  A single press replaces \"!!\", later presses "
"replace \"!-3\" and the like."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:171
msgid ""
"If the line you want is far back in the history, type any part of the line "
"and then press Up one or more times.  This will filter the recalled lines to "
"ones that include this text, and you will get to the line you want much "
"faster.  This replaces \"!vi\", \"!?bar.c\" and the like."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:173
msgid ""
":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`↑` recalls individual arguments, starting from the "
"last argument in the last executed line.  A single press replaces \"!$\", "
"later presses replace \"!!:4\" and such. As an alternate key binding, :kbd:"
"`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`.` can be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:175
msgid ""
"If the argument you want is far back in history (e.g. 2 lines back - that's "
"a lot of words!), type any part of it and then press :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:"
"`↑`.  This will show only arguments containing that part and you will get "
"what you want much faster.  Try it out, this is very convenient!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:177
msgid ""
"If you want to reuse several arguments from the same line (\"!!:3*\" and the "
"like), consider recalling the whole line and removing what you don't need (:"
"kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`D` and :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`Backspace` are your "
"friends)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:179
msgid ""
"See :ref:`documentation <editor>` for more details about line editing in "
"fish."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:182
msgid "How do I run a subcommand? The backtick doesn't work!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:183
msgid "``fish`` uses parentheses for subcommands. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:185
msgid ""
"for i in (ls)\n"
"    echo $i\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:189
msgid ""
"It also supports the familiar ``$()`` syntax, even in quotes. Backticks are "
"not supported because they are discouraged even in POSIX shells. They nest "
"poorly and are hard to tell from single quotes (``''``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:192
msgid "My command (pkg-config) gives its output as a single long string?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:193
msgid ""
"Unlike other shells, fish splits command substitutions only on newlines, not "
"spaces or tabs or the characters in $IFS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:195
msgid "That means if you run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:199
msgid "count (printf '%s ' a b c)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:202
msgid ""
"It will print ``1``, because the \"a b c \" is used in one piece. But if you "
"do"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:206
msgid "count (printf '%s\\n' a b c)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:208
msgid ""
"it will print ``3``, because it gave ``count`` the arguments \"a\", \"b\" "
"and \"c\" separately."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:210
msgid ""
"In the overwhelming majority of cases, splitting on spaces is unwanted, so "
"this is an improvement. This is why you hear about problems with filenames "
"with spaces, after all."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:212
msgid ""
"However sometimes, especially with ``pkg-config`` and related tools, "
"splitting on spaces is needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:214
msgid "In these cases use ``string split -n \" \"`` like::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:216
msgid ""
"g++ example_01.cpp (pkg-config --cflags --libs gtk+-2.0 | string split -n \" "
"\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:218
msgid "The ``-n`` is so empty elements are removed like POSIX shells would do."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:221
msgid "How do I get the exit status of a command?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:222
msgid ""
"Use the ``$status`` variable. This replaces the ``$?`` variable used in "
"other shells."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:226
msgid ""
"somecommand\n"
"if test $status -eq 7\n"
"    echo \"That's my lucky number!\"\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:232
msgid ""
"If you are just interested in success or failure, you can run the command "
"directly as the if-condition::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:234
msgid ""
"if somecommand\n"
"    echo \"Command succeeded\"\n"
"else\n"
"    echo \"Command failed\"\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:241
msgid ""
"Or if you just want to do one command in case the first succeeded or failed, "
"use ``and`` or ``or``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:243
msgid ""
"somecommand\n"
"or someothercommand"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:246
msgid ""
"See the :ref:`Conditions <syntax-conditional>` and the documentation for :"
"doc:`test <cmds/test>` and :doc:`if <cmds/if>` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:249
msgid "My command prints \"No matches for wildcard\" but works in bash"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:251
msgid ""
"In short: :ref:`quote <quotes>` or :ref:`escape <escapes>` the wildcard::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:253
msgid "scp user@ip:/dir/\"string-*\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:255
msgid ""
"When fish sees an unquoted ``*``, it performs :ref:`wildcard expansion "
"<expand-wildcard>`. That means it tries to match filenames to the given "
"string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:257
msgid ""
"If the wildcard doesn't match any files, fish prints an error instead of "
"running the command::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:259
msgid ""
"> echo *this*does*not*exist\n"
"fish: No matches for wildcard '*this*does*not*exist'. See `help expand`.\n"
"echo *this*does*not*exist\n"
"     ^"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:264
msgid ""
"Now, bash also tries to match files in this case, but when it doesn't find a "
"match, it passes along the literal wildcard string instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:266
msgid "That means that commands like the above"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:268
msgid "scp user@ip:/dir/string-*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:272
msgid "or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:274
msgid "apt install postgres-*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:278
msgid ""
"appear to work, because most of the time the string doesn't match and so it "
"passes along the ``string-*``, which is then interpreted by the receiving "
"program."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:280
msgid ""
"But it also means that these commands can stop working at any moment once a "
"matching file is encountered (because it has been created or the command is "
"executed in a different working directory), and to deal with that bash needs "
"workarounds like"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:282
msgid ""
"for f in ./*.mpg; do\n"
"      # We need to test if the file really exists because\n"
"      # the wildcard might have failed to match.\n"
"      test -f \"$f\" || continue\n"
"      mympgviewer \"$f\"\n"
"done"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:291
msgid "(from http://mywiki.wooledge.org/BashFAQ/004)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:293
msgid ""
"For these reasons, fish does not do this, and instead expects asterisks to "
"be quoted or escaped if they aren't supposed to be expanded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:295
msgid "This is similar to bash's \"failglob\" option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:298
msgid ""
"I accidentally entered a directory path and fish changed directory. What "
"happened?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:299
msgid ""
"If fish is unable to locate a command with a given name, and it starts with "
"``.``, ``/`` or ``~``, fish will test if a directory of that name exists. If "
"it does, it assumes that you want to change your directory. For example, the "
"fastest way to switch to your home directory is to simply press ``~`` and "
"enter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:302
msgid "The open command doesn't work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:303
msgid ""
"The ``open`` command uses the MIME type database and the ``.desktop`` files "
"used by Gnome and KDE to identify filetypes and default actions. If at least "
"one of these environments is installed, but the open command is not working, "
"this probably means that the relevant files are installed in a non-standard "
"location. Consider :ref:`asking for more help <more-help>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:308
msgid "Why won't SSH/SCP/rsync connect properly when fish is my login shell?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:310
msgid ""
"This problem may show up as messages like \"``Received message too long``\", "
"\"``open terminal failed: not a terminal``\", \"``Bad packet length``\", or "
"\"``Connection refused``\" with strange output in "
"``ssh_exchange_identification`` messages in the debug log."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:314
msgid ""
"This usually happens because fish reads the :ref:`user configuration file "
"<configuration>` (``~/.config/fish/config.fish``) *always*, whether it's in "
"an interactive or login or non-interactive or non-login shell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:317
msgid ""
"This simplifies matters, but it also means when config.fish generates "
"output, it will do that even in non-interactive shells like the one ssh/scp/"
"rsync start when they connect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:319
msgid ""
"Anything in config.fish that produces output should be guarded with ``status "
"is-interactive`` (or ``status is-login`` if you prefer)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:322
msgid ""
"if status is-interactive\n"
"  ...\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:326
msgid ""
"The same applies for example when you start ``tmux`` in config.fish without "
"guards, which will cause a message like ``sessions should be nested with "
"care, unset $TMUX to force``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:331
msgid ""
"I'm getting weird graphical glitches (a staircase effect, ghost characters, "
"cursor in the wrong position,...)?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:332
msgid ""
"In a terminal, the application running inside it and the terminal itself "
"need to agree on the width of characters in order to handle cursor movement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:334
msgid ""
"This is more important to fish than other shells because features like "
"syntax highlighting and autosuggestions are implemented by moving the cursor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:336
msgid ""
"Sometimes, there is disagreement on the width. There are numerous causes and "
"fixes for this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:338
msgid ""
"It is possible the character is simply too new for your system to know - in "
"this case you need to refrain from using it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:339
msgid ""
"Fish or your terminal might not know about the character or handle it wrong "
"- in this case fish or your terminal needs to be fixed, or you need to "
"update to a fixed version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:340
msgid ""
"The character has an \"ambiguous\" width and fish thinks that means a width "
"of X while your terminal thinks it's Y. In this case you either need to "
"change your terminal's configuration or set $fish_ambiguous_width to the "
"correct value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:341
msgid ""
"The character is an emoji and the host system only supports Unicode 8, while "
"you are running the terminal on a system that uses Unicode >= 9. In this "
"case set $fish_emoji_width to 2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:343
msgid "This also means that a few things are unsupportable:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:345
msgid ""
"Non-monospace fonts - there is *no way* for fish to figure out what width a "
"specific character has as it has no influence on the terminal's font "
"rendering."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:346
msgid ""
"Different widths for multiple ambiguous width characters - there is no way "
"for fish to know which width you assign to each character."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:351
msgid "Uninstalling fish"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:352
msgid ""
"If you want to uninstall fish, first make sure fish is not set as your "
"shell. Run ``chsh -s /bin/bash`` if you are not sure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:354
msgid ""
"If you installed it with a package manager, just use that package manager's "
"uninstall function. If you built fish yourself, assuming you installed it "
"to /usr/local, do this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:356
msgid ""
"rm -Rf /usr/local/etc/fish /usr/local/share/fish ~/.config/fish\n"
"rm /usr/local/share/man/man1/fish*.1\n"
"cd /usr/local/bin\n"
"rm -f fish fish_indent"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:362
msgid "Where can I find extra tools for fish?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:363
msgid ""
"The fish user community extends fish in unique and useful ways via scripts "
"that aren't always appropriate for bundling with the fish package. Typically "
"because they solve a niche problem unlikely to appeal to a broad audience. "
"You can find those extensions, including prompts, themes and useful "
"functions, in various third-party repositories. These include:"
